.TH "Intl.Locale.region" "JS" "May 31, 2024" "JavaScript" "JavaScript Reference Manual"
.SH NAME
Intl.Locale.region \- Intl.Locale.prototype.region
.SH SYNOPSIS
The \f[B]\f[CB]region\f[B]\f[R] accessor property of
\f[CR]Intl.Locale\f[R] instances returns the region of the world
(usually a country) associated with this locale.
.SH DESCRIPTION
Region is one of the core attributes of a locale.
It allows selection for differences between the same language in, say,
different countries.
For example, English is spoken in the United Kingdom and the United
States of America, but there are differences in spelling and other
language conventions between those two countries.
Knowing the locale\[cq]s region helps JavaScript programmers make sure
that the content from their sites and applications is correctly
displayed when viewed from different areas of the world.
The \f[CR]region\f[R] property\[cq]s value is set at construction time,
either through the \f[CR]region\f[R] subtag (third part if
\f[CR]script\f[R] is present, second part otherwise) of the locale
identifier or through the \f[CR]region\f[R] option of the
\f[CR]Intl.Locale()\f[R] constructor.
The latter takes priority if they are both present; and if neither is
present, the property has value \f[CR]undefined\f[R].
.PP
The set accessor of \f[CR]region\f[R] is \f[CR]undefined\f[R].
You cannot change this property directly.
.SH EXAMPLES
Like other locale subtags, the region can be added to the
\f[CR]Intl.Locale\f[R] object via the locale string, or a configuration
object argument to the constructor.
.SS Adding a region via the locale string
The region, if present, is the third part (if \f[CR]script\f[R] is
present, second part otherwise) of a valid Unicode language identifier
string, and can be added to the initial locale identifier string that is
passed into the \f[CR]Intl.Locale()\f[R] constructor.
Note that the region is not a required part of a locale identifier.
.IP
.EX
\f[B]const\f[R] locale = \f[B]new\f[R] Intl.Locale(\[dq]en\-Latn\-US\[dq]);
console.log(locale.region); \f[I]// Prints \[dq]US\[dq]\f[R]
.EE
.SS Adding a region via the configuration object argument
The \f[CR]Intl.Locale()\f[R] constructor has an optional configuration
object argument.
Set the \f[CR]region\f[R] property of the configuration object to your
desired region, and then pass it into the constructor.
.IP
.EX
\f[B]const\f[R] locale = \f[B]new\f[R] Intl.Locale(\[dq]fr\-Latn\[dq], { region: \[dq]FR\[dq] });
console.log(locale.region); \f[I]// Prints \[dq]FR\[dq]\f[R]
.EE
